.TH CLIPMAN 1 "February 2025" "clipman 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
clipman \- Simple clipboard manager for Linux (X11)
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBclipman\fR \fICOMMAND\fR [\fIOPTIONS\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
ClipMan is a lightweight clipboard manager for Linux X11. It runs in the
background, monitoring clipboard changes and maintaining a persistent history
of copied items.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
\fBstart\fR
Start the clipboard daemon in the background.
.TP
\fBrun\fR
Run the daemon in the foreground (for systemd).
.TP
\fBstop\fR
Stop the clipboard daemon.
.TP
\fBstatus\fR
Show daemon status and history count.
.TP
\fBhistory\fR [\fB\-n\fR \fINUM\fR]
Show clipboard history. Default: 20 entries.
.TP
\fBselect\fR \fIINDEX\fR
Copy a history entry to clipboard by index.
.TP
\fBpin\fR \fIINDEX\fR
Toggle pin status of a history entry.
.TP
\fBpick\fR
Interactive selection using rofi, fzf, or manual input.
.TP
\fBclear\fR
Clear clipboard history (keeps pinned items).
.TP
\fBget\fR
Print current clipboard content.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.config/clipman/history.json
Clipboard history storage.
.TP
.I ~/.config/clipman/clipman.pid
Daemon PID file.
.SH GUI
The clipboard picker GUI can be launched with the \fBclipman-gui\fR command.
It provides a searchable list of clipboard entries with support for pinning
and deleting items.
.TP
Bind Alt+V (or your preferred shortcut) to \fBclipman-gui\fR for quick access.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
\fBclipman-gui\fR(1), \fBxclip\fR(1)
